'''Obihiro Shrine''' (帯廣神社, ''Obihiro jinja'') is a [[Shinto]] shrine located in [[Obihiro, Hokkaido]]. Erected in 1910, it is dedicated to the [[kami]] Ōkuni-mitama no mikoto (大國魂神), [[Ōkuninushi]] no mikoto (大那牟遲神), and [[Sukunabikona]] no mikoto (少彦名神). Its festival is on September 24. Obihiro Shrine was formerly Ranked as a prefectural shrine.

== History ==
In [[:en:1883|1883]] (Meiji 16), the pioneering group "Bansei-sha" relocated to Obihiro and started performing rites around [[:en:1885|1885]] (Meiji 18). By [[:en:1890|1890]] (Meiji 23), a small shrine was built and called "Obihiro Shrine." This is considered the origin of the current shrine. However, Obihiro Shrine acknowledges that the relationship between Bansei-sha's "Obihiro Shrine" and the present shrine is unclear.

In [[:en:1909|1909]] (Meiji 42), a decision was made to establish a new shrine at the current location, and a shrine establishment petition was submitted to the Hokkaido Government in [[:en:1910|1910]] (Meiji 43). On September 24th of the same year, spirits were transferred from Sapporo Shrine (now [[Hokkaido Shrine]]). The shrine was designated as a Mukakusha (unranked shrine) in [[:en:1911|1911]] (Meiji 44), elevated to Gōsha (village shrine) in [[:en:1918|1918]] (Taishō 7), and further promoted to Prefectural Shrine in [[:en:1930|1930]] (Shōwa 5). In [[:en:1976|1976]] (Shōwa 51), it was included in the list of Beppyo Shrines under the Association of Shinto Shrines.

== In Popular Culture ==
* The manga and anime series [[Silver Spoon]] features "Dai Ezo Shrine," modeled after Obihiro Shrine. It is depicted as the setting for the protagonist and heroine's first date.

