In [[:en:1909|1909]] (Meiji 42), a decision was made to establish a new shrine at the current location, and a shrine establishment petition was submitted to the Hokkaido Government in [[:en:1910|1910]] (Meiji 43). On September 24th of the same year, spirits were transferred from Sapporo Shrine (now [[:en:Hokkaido Shrine|Hokkaido Shrine]]). The shrine was designated as a Mukakusha (unranked shrine) in [[:en:1911|1911]] (Meiji 44), elevated to Gōsha (village shrine) in [[:en:1918|1918]] (Taishō 7), and further promoted to Prefectural Shrine in [[:en:1930|1930]] (Shōwa 5). In [[:en:1976|1976]] (Shōwa 51), it was included in the list of Beppyo Shrines under the Association of Shinto Shrines.

== In Popular Culture ==
* The manga and anime series [[:en:Silver Spoon|Silver Spoon]] features "Dai Ezo Shrine," modeled after Obihiro Shrine. It is depicted as the setting for the protagonist and heroine's first date.

