'''Obihiro Shrine''' (帯廣神社, ''Obihiro jinja'') is a [[Shinto]] shrine located in [[:en:Obihiro, Hokkaido|Obihiro, Hokkaido]]. Erected in 1910, it is dedicated to the [[kami]] Ōkuni-mitama no mikoto (大國魂神), [[Ōkuninushi]] no mikoto (大那牟遲神), and [[Sukunabikona]] no mikoto (少彦名神). Its festival is on September 24. Obihiro Shrine was formerly Ranked as a prefectural shrine.

== History ==
In {{ill|1883|en|1883|WD=Q7816|lt=1883|1=1883}} (Meiji 16), the pioneering group "Bansei-sha" relocated to Obihiro and started performing rites around {{ill|1885|en|1885|WD=Q7821|lt=1885|1=1885}} (Meiji 18). By {{ill|1890|en|1890|WD=Q7832|lt=1890|1=1890}} (Meiji 23), a small shrine was built and called "Obihiro Shrine." This is considered the origin of the current shrine. However, Obihiro Shrine acknowledges that the relationship between Bansei-sha's "Obihiro Shrine" and the present shrine is unclear.

In {{ill|1909|en|1909|WD=Q2057|lt=1909|1=1909}} (Meiji 42), a decision was made to establish a new shrine at the current location, and a shrine establishment petition was submitted to the Hokkaido Government in {{ill|1910|en|1910|WD=Q2075|lt=1910|1=1910}} (Meiji 43). On September 24th of the same year, spirits were transferred from Sapporo Shrine (now [[:en:Hokkaido Shrine|Hokkaido Shrine]]). The shrine was designated as a Mukakusha (unranked shrine) in {{ill|1911|en|1911|WD=Q2076|lt=1911|1=1911}} (Meiji 44), elevated to Gōsha (village shrine) in {{ill|1918|en|1918|WD=Q2094|lt=1918|1=1918}} (Taishō 7), and further promoted to Prefectural Shrine in {{ill|1930|en|1930|WD=Q18787|lt=1930|1=1930}} (Shōwa 5). In {{ill|1976|en|1976|WD=Q2480|lt=1976|1=1976}} (Shōwa 51), it was included in the list of Beppyo Shrines under the Association of Shinto Shrines.

== In Popular Culture ==
* The manga and anime series [[:en:Silver Spoon|Silver Spoon]] features "Dai Ezo Shrine," modeled after Obihiro Shrine. It is depicted as the setting for the protagonist and heroine's first date.

